Laravel Gates allow you to define authorization logic in your code, enabling
granular control over user permissions.


GATE STRUCTURE AND BOOTING

The AuthServiceProvider is responsible for the initialization of your gates and
policies.

Gates utilize two main functions:

 1. define: This method specifies the gate's ability and the related callback
    function that checks for the user's permission.

    Gate::define('update-post', function ($user, $post) {
        return $user->id === $post->user_id;
    });


 2. allows: This function is used in the controller to directly test the user's
    ability.

    if ($request->user()->can('update-post', $post)) {
        // User has permission to update the post
    }



MULTIPLE PARAMETER GATES

Gates can take more than the default two parameters: the authenticated user and
the relevant model/object. Additional parameters, if needed, can be supplied in
the can and allows methods.

Gate::define('publish-post', function ($user, $post, $isPublished) {
    return $user->id === $post->user_id && !$isPublished;
});

if (Gate::allows('publish-post', [$post, true])) {
    $post->publish();
}



GLOBALLY AUTHORIZED CHECKS

Globally authorized checks, accessible via Gate::authorize, initiate the Laravel
Exception handling mechanism when a user lacks the required permission, allowing
for a more streamlined and consistent approach to authorization.

Gate::authorize('update-post', $post);

// No need for explicit permission checks here, will throw an authorization exception if not allowed




BLADE TEMPLATE DIRECTIVES

Blade templates feature succinct directives for permission checks.

 * Blade IF: A simple if-else statement that only displays the content if the
   user possesses the permission.

   @can('update-post', $post)
       <button>Edit Post</button>
   @endcan


 * Blade Unless: Content is displayed only if the user doesn't have the
   permission.

   @cannot('update-post', $post)
       <p>Sorry, you can't edit this post.</p>
   @endcannot



FORM REQUESTS FOR BACK-END VALIDATION

In Laravel, Form Requests assist with back-end validation. To ensure that only
authorized users can perform actions, include an authorize method.

class PostUpdateRequest extends FormRequest
{
    // ...

    public function authorize()
    {
        return $this->user()->can('update-post', $this->post());
    }
}



CONCLUSION

Gates in Laravel are a powerful tool that allows for fine-grained control over
user authorizations, whether it be handling multiple parameter checks or
authorizing actions within Form Requests. Their convenient integrations with
Blade templates ensure consistency in your application's UI.

Laravel Policies provide a streamlined way to authorize actions based on user
roles. Instead of scattering authorization logic throughout your application,
Laravel suggests consolidating these checks within Policy Classes dedicated to
specific resource types.


KEY COMPONENTS

 1. Authority Figure: The policies manage who can do what, while the gate serves
    as a global authority for permission checks.

 2. Resource Guardian: A policy class usually guards access rights for a
    particular resource like a SunflowerPolicy for guarding Sunflower resources.


WORKING TOGETHER

The gateway is your starting point for validation, while the policy acts as a
specialized checkpoint. When a user attempts an action:

 1. The gateway evaluates any global checks using the authorize method. It stops
    further execution if the check fails

 2. If the global authorization passes, the gateway checks the related policy
    with the authorize method. The policy verifies the resource-specific
    permission


AUTHORIZATION CONSIDERATIONS

 * Conciseness and Simplicity: Unclutter your codebase by focusing policy checks
   in designated classes.

 * Elevated Readability: Policies make it evident which rules apply to different
   resources.

 * Flexibility and Customization: They empower you to tailor nuanced permissions
   for various user types.

 * Respect for Middleware: Policies work in tandem with middleware to ensure
   holistic security across your app.


POLICY CLASSES IN ACTION

To demonstrate, consider a Task object that you need to protect based on user
roles:

TASKCONTROLLER

Here is your TaskController:

use App\Task;
use Illuminate\Support\Facades\Gate;

class TaskController extends Controller
{
    public function complete($taskId)
    {
        $task = Task::findOrFail($taskId);

        Gate::authorize('complete-task', $task);

        $task->is_complete = 1;
        $task->save();

        return redirect('/tasks');
    }
}


POLICY: TASKPOLICY

Your TaskPolicy manages Task-related permissions:

namespace App\Policies;

use App\User;
use App\Task;
use Illuminate\Auth\Access\HandlesAuthorization;

class TaskPolicy
{
    use HandlesAuthorization;

    public function completeTask(User $user, Task $task)
    {
        return $user->id === $task->assigned_to;
    }
}


REGISTERING POLICIES

Here is the code to register the TaskPolicy:

In AuthServiceProvider:

use App\Task;
use App\Policies\TaskPolicy;

class AuthServiceProvider extends ServiceProvider
{
    protected $policies = [
        Task::class => TaskPolicy::class,
    ];
}



CODE ANALYSIS

 * The controller leverages authorization through the Gate facade, promoting
   clear code readability and centralized policy enforcement.

 * The TaskPolicy contains the logic for completeTask, making it effortless to
   comprehend who can complete a task.

 * In the AuthServiceProvider, the Task::class mapping ensures the associated
   policy (TaskPolicy) safeguards Task resources.

In Laravel, the @can and @cannot Blade directives provide an easy way to control
