Laravel uses a service container or IoC container to manage dependencies and
bind them either in a delegated or contextual manner.


STEPS TO BIND SERVICES INTO THE CONTAINER

 1. Choose the Binding Method: Depending on the use case, you can bind services
    using either bind or singleton.

 2. Select a Contextual Binding if Necessary: For more dynamic use-cases, you'll
    need to use a contextual binding with either the when method or the concrete
    method.

 3. Define the Binding in a Service Provider or Bootstrapping: This can be done
    in the register method of a service provider or in the boot method.

 4. Ensure Autoloading: Laravel applications built using Composer usually
    auto-load classes. However, make sure that the classes to be bound are
    autoloaded without conflict.


CODE EXAMPLE: BASIC BINDING

Here is the implementation:

1_The Service provider Class_:

use Illuminate\Support\ServiceProvider;

class MyServiceProvider extends ServiceProvider
{
    public function register()
    {
        // Bind as Singleton
        $this->app->singleton('myService', function ($app) {
            return new MyService();
        });

        // Bind as Instantiator
        $this->app->bind('myInstantiableService', function ($app) {
            return new MyInstantiableService();
        });

        // Targeting an Interface
        $this->app->bind(MyRepositoryInterface::class, MyRepository::class);
    }
}


2_The class MyService and MyInstantiableService are added too_:

class MyService {
    //service logic
}

class MyInstantiableService {
    //service logic
}



CODE EXAMPLE: CONTEXTUAL BINDING

Here is the implementation:

1_Nested Binding_:

$this->app->when(PhotoController::class)
          ->needs(Filesystem::class)
          ->give(function () {
              return Storage::disk('local');
          });


2_Targeting Specific Contexts:

$this->app->when(DellMonitor::class)
          ->needs(MonitorContract::class)
          ->give(function () {
              return new DellMonitor;
          });

$this->app->when(HPMonitor::class)
          ->needs(MonitorContract::class)
          ->give(function () {
              return new HPMonitor;
          });

