CODE EXAMPLE: DEFINING AN API RESOURCE CLASS

Here is the Laravel PHP code:

class UserResource extends JsonResource
{
    public function toArray($request)
    {
        // Define resource data
        return [
            'id' => $this->id,
            'name' => $this->name,
            'email' => $this->email,
            'created_at' => $this->created_at,
            'posts_count' => $this->posts->count(),  // Example of a computed attribute
        ];
    }

    public function with($request)
    {
        return [
            'meta' => [
                'version' => 1.0,
            ],
        ];
    }
}



BEST PRACTICE: CACHING

Implement caching for resource-intensive queries, fetching these from cache
where possible to minimize database hits and client response times. Depending on
requirements, you can utilize Laravel's caching mechanisms:

 1. Eager-caching model data.
 2. Optimizing query retrievals with JSON resource caching and ETags.


CODE EXAMPLE: IMPLEMENTING JSON RESOURCE CACHING

Here is the Laravel PHP code:

use Illuminate\Support\Facades\Cache;
use Illuminate\Http\Request;
use Illuminate\Http\Resources\Json\ResourceResponse;
use App\Models\User;

class UserResource extends JsonResource
{
    // ... (previous methods and properties unchanged)

    public function toResponse($request)
    {
        $cacheKey = 'user_' . $this->id;

        return Cache::remember($cacheKey, 3600, function () use ($request) {
            return parent::toResponse($request);
        });
    }

    public static function collection($resource)
    {
        return new CachedUserResourceCollection(User::all());
    }
}

class CachedUserResourceCollection extends ResourceCollection
{
    public function toResponse($request)
    {
        $cacheKey = 'users_collection';

        return Cache::remember($cacheKey, 3600, function () use ($request) {
            return parent::toResponse($request);
        });
    }
}

Laravel Collections provide a fluent, expressive, and array-like way to interact
with data in Laravel. Behind the scenes, they are implemented using specialized
classes like Illuminate\Support\Collection.


CORE COLLECTION METHODS

 * Each: Iterates through the collection and performs a function for each item.
 * Map: Applies a callback to each item and returns a modified collection.
 * Filter: Returns a new collection with items that pass a given truth test.
 * Reject: Opposite of filter - items that fail the truth test are returned.
 * Reduce: Boils down the collection to a single value via a callback.
 * Merge: Merges the collection with another.


CHAINING METHODS

One of the many strengths of Laravel Collections is method chaining, which
enables you to call multiple operations on a collection in one line, making the
code more readable and concise.

Here are a few examples:

CHAINING METHODS WITH PRACTICAL EXAMPLES

 * Empty: Checks if a collection is empty.

   $isEmpty = collect([1, 2, 3])->filter(function ($value) {
       return $value > 10;
   })->isEmpty();


 * Map and flatten: Maps each item to a new collection and then flattens the
   result by a depth of one. This is useful for extracting values to a flat
   list.

   $result = collect([1, 2, 3])->map(function ($item) {
       return ['count' => $item];
   })->flatten(1);


 * Sum: Sums the values in the collection.

   $total = collect([1, 2, 3])->sum();


 * Unique: Returns all unique items in the collection.

   $unique = collect([1, 1, 2, 2, 3, 3])->unique();


 * Take: Returns the first n items.

   $firstTwo = collect([1, 2, 3, 4, 5])->take(2);


 * TakeWhile: Returns items from the beginning of the collection until the
   provided function returns false.

   $lessThanThree = collect([1, 2, 3, 4, 5])->takeWhile(function ($value) {
       return $value < 3;
   });


 * Count: Returns the number of items in the collection.

   $count = collect([1, 2, 3])->count();


 * Max and min: Return the maximum and minimum values in the collection. Here
   are the code samples:

   $max = collect([1, 2, 3])->max();
   $min = collect([1, 2, 3])->min();


 * Contains: Checks if a collection contains a given item.

   $contains = collect([1, 2, 3])->contains(2);


 * Pluck: Extracts a list of attribute values from a collection of objects.

   $collection = collect([
       ['product_id' => 'prod-100', 'name' => 'Laptop'],
       ['product_id' => 'prod-200', 'name' => 'Phone'],
   ]);
   $plucked = $collection->pluck('name');



EAGER CHAINING

In addition to the standard chaining, there is a concept of eager chaining in
Laravel, which can speed up operations on large collections or across multiple
queries.

Eager chaining methods are prefixed with "eager" and include eagerMap,
eagerFilter, eagerReject, eagerTake, eagerEach, and more. These operations are
executed in one iteration, potentially improving performance.


CODE EXAMPLE: EAGER CHAINING

Here is the code example:

$users = User::all();

// Eagerly load certain relations using chaining for performance
$users->eagerLoad(['posts', 'comments']);



COLLECTION WRAPPERS

CALL METHOD

The call method invokes a method on each instance of the collection, passing any
additional arguments to it.

Here is the code example:

$collection = collect([
    new class {
        public function prefixName($name)
        {
            return "{$name}-ref";
        }
    },
    new class {
        public function getName()
        {
            return 'ref';
        }
    },
]);

// Output: ['oref', 'ref']
$collection->call('getName')->map->prefixName('o')->all();



HIGHER-ORDER MESSAGES

Higher-order messages permit you to chain methods on a collection of objects.
This mechanism is achieved using the toBase method.

Here is the code example:

$collection = collect([
   new class { 
       public function meals() { return collect(['taylor', 'matt', 'jeff']); }
   },
   new class {
       public function meals() { return collect(['milo', 'matt']); }
   },
]);

// Output : ['taylor', 'matt', 'milo', 'matt', 'matt', 'jeff']
$result = $collection->flatMap->meals()->unique()->values()->all();

While Laravel comes pre-equipped with collections to manipulate data, you might
have requirements that go beyond the built-in methods. Laravel provides a
flexible way to extend collections with custom methods to cater to such
specialized needs.


STEPS FOR CUSTOM METHOD CREATION

 1. Create a Service Provider: Start by generating a service provider for
    collections. This can be done using artisan.

 2. Register the Provider: Update the providers array in the config/app.php
    configuration file.

 3. Define the Method: In the service provider, create the custom method using
    Collection::mixin().

 4. Make the Method Accessible: Use @mixin in PHPDoc to make the custom method
    accessible within your codebase.


CODE EXAMPLE: CUSTOM COLLECTION METHOD

Here is the PHP code:

// artisan command for generating the service provider
// php artisan make:provider CollectionMacroServiceProvider


CollectionMacroServiceProvider.php

namespace App\Providers;

use Illuminate\Support\ServiceProvider;
use Illuminate\Support\Collection;

class CollectionMacroServiceProvider extends ServiceProvider
{
    public function boot()
    {
        Collection::macro('sumAndSquare', function ($column) {
            return $this->sum($column) ** 2;
        });
    }

    public function register()
    {
        // 
    }
}


config/app.php

'providers' => [
    // Other Service Providers
    App\Providers\CollectionMacroServiceProvider::class,
],


Usage

use Illuminate\Support\Collection;

$numbers = collect([1, 2, 3, 4, 5]);

$sumSquared = $numbers->sumAndSquare();
// Output: 225 (1+2+3+4+5)^2 = 225


In this example, the custom method sumAndSquare calculates the sum of a column
in the collection and squares the result, demonstrating how you can extend
Laravel collections for more tailored data manipulation.

Lazy Collections are a feature in Laravel that helps manage large datasets more
efficiently. It reduces memory consumption and improves performance by executing
operations on a dataset only when necessary.


ELOQUENT QUERIES WITH LAZY LOADING

Instead of returning all records in the database that match a particular
criteria, you can utilize the lazy method to utilize Lazy Collections. It can be
particularly beneficial when working with applications that contain an extensive
amount of data or are accessed by a multitude of concurrent users.

Here is an example to demonstrate how you can effectively merge, transform, and
finally limit the data being returned:

// Eager loading data and then reducing it to a limited dataset
$limitedPosts = Post::with('comments')->get()->take(5);



OPERATIONS ON COLLECTIONS

You can take advantage of map, filter, reduce, and other functional programming
methods through a fluent interface. The code presented below uses the filter
method to select users of a certain age and email domain:

$users->filter(function($user) {
    return $user->age > 21 && Str::endsWith($user->email, '@example.com');
});



SUPPORTS ITERABLE DATA TYPES

Lazy Collections provide support for different iterable data types, such as
generators, which play a vital role in optimizing the memory footprint when
managing large datasets.

Below is a code to validate unique emails across an array of users and a
collection of users using a generator:

// Array Validation
$uniqueEmails = collect($users)->unique('email')->count() === count($users);

// Generator Validation
function getUniqueEmails($users) {
    $uniqueEmails = [];
    foreach ($users as $user) {
        if (!in_array($user->email, $uniqueEmails)) {
            $uniqueEmails[] = $user->email;
            yield $user->email;
        }
    }
}



ELOQUENT RELATIONSHIPS

Lazy Collections can also be leveraged in Eloquent relationships, allowing you
to further fine-tune the data you want to access or manipulate.

Here is a code to show how you can access the posts' comments and further refine
them:

// Access posts with lazy-loading enabled
$posts = Post::all()->lazy();

// Retrieve posts and comments in batches of 10
$posts->chunk(10)->each(function($chunk) {
    $chunk->load('comments');
});



PRACTICAL SCENARIO:

Consider a situation where you need to retrieve recent users from the database
and their latest posts. You can achieve this efficiently using chunkById and
lazy methods.

$users = User::where('created_at', '>=', now()->subDays(7))->orderBy('id')->lazy();

$users->chunkById(1000, function($chunk) {
    $chunk->load('posts');
});


In this code, users created in the last 7 days are retrieved and chunks of 1000
users are loaded with their posts. Lazy loading ensures only the required users
and posts are loaded during the process.

When tasks in a Laravel queue system encounter errors, they are marked as
"failed" and can be managed accordingly.


VISIBILITY OF FAILED JOBS

In a Laravel system, you can manage failed tasks from either the command line or
the web interface provided by Laravel Horizon.


USING THE ARTISAN CONSOLE

The queue:failed Artisan command offers a range of functionalities to manage
failed jobs:

 * queue:failed - Lists all failed jobs.
 * queue:retry {id*} - Retries one or multiple failed jobs.
 * queue:forget {id*} - Deletes one or multiple failed jobs.
 * queue:flush - Deletes all failed jobs.


LARAVEL HORIZON

Laravel Horizon provides a dashboard where you can:

 * Monitor the queue and jobs in real time.
 * Manage failed jobs from the dashboard itself.


CUSTOM NOTIFICATIONS FOR FAILED JOBS

To receive notifications when a job fails, Laravel provides a failed method on
the job itself. You can customize this method to send notifications through
different channels, such as email or SMS.


WHAT HAPPENS WHEN JOBS FAIL

When a job fails more times than its defined attempts, it's marked as failed in
the queue. Laravel also logs the error and can handle the failure through
configured policies.

CODE EXAMPLE: JOB WITH CUSTOM FAILURE HANDLING

Here is the Laravel job with custom failure handling:

use Illuminate\Contracts\Queue\ShouldQueue;
use Illuminate\Bus\Queueable;
use Illuminate\Queue\InteractsWithQueue;
use Illuminate\Queue\SerializesModels;

class SampleJob implements ShouldQueue
{
    use InteractsWithQueue, Queueable, SerializesModels;

    /**
     * The maximum number of attempts the job should take before it's marked as failed.
     *
     * @var int
     */
    public $tries = 3;

    public $maxExceptions = 1;

    /**
     * The handle method for the job.
     *
     * @return void
     */
    public function handle()
    {
        // Process the job
    }

    /**
     * The failed method to handle job failure.
     *
     * @param  \Throwable  $exception
     * @return void
     */
    public function failed(\Throwable $exception = null)
    {
        // Custom failure handling, e.g., log the error or send a notification
    }
}

