Laravel Notifications provide a unified channel for sending informative messages
to users via email, SMS, webhooks, and more. They also offer a level of
abstraction, permitting easy swappability of delivery mediums.


KEY COMPONENTS

 * Notification: A message intended for user delivery.
 * Notification Channels: Directs where and how notifications are delivered
   (e.g., mail, database, or slack channels).
 * Routing Logic: Determines the appropriate channel(s) for a particular
   notification type.


NOTIFICATION IN ACTION

Here is a sample code snippet of a WelcomeNotification for new users:

namespace App\Notifications;

use Illuminate\Bus\Queueable;
use Illuminate\Contracts\Queue\ShouldQueue;
use Illuminate\Notifications\Messages\MailMessage;
use Illuminate\Notifications\Notification;

class WelcomeNotification extends Notification
{
    use Queueable;

    public function via($notifiable)
    {
        // Determines notification channels
        return ['mail', 'database'];
    }

    public function toMail($notifiable)
    {
        // Generates email message
        return (new MailMessage)
            ->greeting('Welcome to Our App!')
            ->line('Thank you for joining.');
    }

    public function toArray($notifiable)
    {
        // Data to be stored in the database
        return [
            'greeting' => 'Welcome to Our App!',
            'message' => 'Thank you for joining.'
        ];
    }
}



SENDING NOTIFICATIONS

 * To a User or Group: Use the notify() method on the user model or a
   collection.

 * Using Notification Facade: Ideal for users not modeled in the application
   (e.g., when communicating with third-party web services). This pattern also
   offers greater customization.


WRITING CUSTOM CHANNELS

Laravel allows for the development of custom notification channels, giving you
the flexibility to define your preferred notification delivery mechanism.

To create a custom channel:

 1. * Define a via method in your notification class. This method should return
      a collection that may contain values such as mail, database, and your
      custom channel identifier.

    * Implement the necessary channel in the toMail, toDatabase, or other
      appropriate methods.
 2. * Register the custom channel in the via or User::routeNotificationFor
      method. This assists Laravel in determining the channels associated with a
      recipient.
    * Update the notification class.

Here is how you can define a custom channel:

public function via($notifiable)
{
    return ['mail', 'sms', 'custom-channel'];
}



AVAILABLE CHANNELS

Some common notification channels in Laravel include:

 * Mail: For sending emails using Laravel's mail services.
 * Database: Logs notifications in the database for later action.
 * SMS: Routinely notifies users via text messages.
 * Broadcasting: Utilized for real-time notifications via web sockets (For
   example, using Pusher).


NOTIFICATION BEHIND THE SCENES

Laravel's notification system is primarily managed by two key classes:

 * Notifiable: A trait included by models eligible to receive notifications. It
   provides methods necessary for routing notifications.
 * NotificationChannel: This abstract class outlines contract methods that
   should be implemented by each notification channel.

Laravel provides a streamlined approach to sending out notifications across
various channels, ensuring flexibility and ease of use.


LARAVEL NOTIFICATION SYSTEMS

Laravel Notifications facilitate the systematic delivery of messages across
diverse channels, combining efficiency and flexibility.

COMPONENTS OF THE LARAVEL NOTIFICATION SYSTEM

 1. Notification Classes:

    These dedicated classes encapsulate the content and delivery nuances for the
    respective notification medium (email, SMS, database, etc.).

    Example: Sending a "Thank You" email to a user.

    // ThankYouNotification.php
    use Illuminate\Notifications\Notification;
    use Illuminate\Notifications\Messages\MailMessage;

    public function toMail($notifiable){
     return (new MailMessage)->line('Thank you for using our application!');}


 2. Notifiable Entities:

    Any entity that can receive a notification, such as users or custom
    recipients, implements the Illuminate\Contracts\Notifications\Notifiable
    contract.

    Example: Users as notifiable entities.

    class User extends Authenticatable {
        use Notifiable;}


 3. Channels:

    These are delivery methods such as email or SMS used to transmit the
    notification. They are specified in notification classes with via().

    Example: Specifying email as the delivery channel.

    public function via($notifiable){
        return ['mail'];}


 4. Routing:

    By default, notifications are dispatched through Laravel's notification
    dispatcher. However, you can specify custom dispatch routes using the
    routeNotificationFor() method in notifiable entities.

    Example: Overriding the default email channel using a method in the User
    model.

    public function routeNotificationForMail($notification){
        return $this->email_address;}


 5. Dispatchers:

    The notification dispatcher transmits notifications to the designated
    channels.

    Instance Dispatcher: Dispatch notifications using notify() method.

    $user->notify(new ThankYouNotification);


    Facad Dispatcher: Utilize the facade to send notifications.

    Notification::send($user, new ThankYouNotification);


    Mailable: Mailables are the components of a Message. These represent emails.

    * toMail(): This method returns a MailMessage instance, setting up the email
      to be sent.

    Modifying The Message:

    * Subject(): Set the email's subject.
    * greeting(): Define the email's greeting.
    * line(): Append a line of text to the email.
    * action(): Integrate a button with the email.
    * attach(): Add an attachment.
    * lineIf(), actionIf(), view(): Conditional line/app components or specify a
      specific view manually.

    SMS Notifications: These represent simple text notifications sent via
    services like Nexmo.

    * toNexmo(): It transforms the message to one that's suitable for Nexmo's
      API.

    1. Email Notifications: They encapsulate the details required for sending an
       email.

       * toMail($notifiable): This method returns a MailMessage instance that
         sets up an email.
       * toArray($notifiable): Sometimes, you might want to send similar content
         via multiple channels. In that case, the returned array is used for
         notifications like Slack.

    2. Database Notifications: This is used for notification persistence,
       especially useful when you want to keep a record of historical
       notifications. It records the notification in notifications table
       associated with the user of the application.
    * toDatabase($notifiable): Here, you specify what data should be stored in
      the database table with the particular user.

CODE EXAMPLE: SENDING NOTIFICATIONS

Here is the PHP code:


   class ThankYouNotification extends Notification
   {
       public function via($notifiable)
       {
           return ['mail'];
       }

       public function toMail($notifiable)
       {
           return (new MailMessage)
               ->line('Thank you for using our application!');
       }
   }

   public function routeNotificationForMail($notification)
   {
       return $this->email_address;
   }
$user->notify(new ThankYouNotification);

