format and storage mechanism. By default, notifications are stored in an
in-memory collection per user, offering quick access. However, for more robust
and persistent storage, Laravel can utilize databases.

To set up database storage for notifications, it's necessary to implement a few
key elements: the database table, a notification model, and then structure the
Laravel code accordingly.


SET UP DATABASE TABLE AND MODEL

First, let's create the migration to define the table in the database, and then
the Notification model.

MIGRATION FILE DATABASE/MIGRATIONS/XXXX_XX_XX_CREATE_NOTIFICATIONS_TABLE.PHP

use Illuminate\Support\Facades\Schema;
use Illuminate\Database\Schema\Blueprint;
use Illuminate\Database\Migrations\Migration;

class CreateNotificationsTable extends Migration
{
    public function up()
    {
        Schema::create('notifications', function (Blueprint $table) {
            $table->bigIncrements('id');
            $table->string('type');
            $table->morphs('notifiable');
            $table->text('data');
            $table->timestamp('read_at')->nullable();
            $table->timestamps();
        });
    }

    public function down()
    {
        Schema::dropIfExists('notifications');
    }
}


Run the migration: php artisan migrate

MODEL: APP/NOTIFICATION.PHP

use Illuminate\Database\Eloquent\Model;

class Notification extends Model
{
    protected $fillable = ['type', 'notifiable_type', 'notifiable_id', 'data', 'read_at'];
    protected $casts = ['read_at' => 'datetime'];

    public function notifiable()
    {
        return $this->morphTo();
    }
}



ADAPTING THE NOTIFIABLE ENTITY

Your notifiable entities, for instance, users, need to be set up correctly to
connect with the notifications table.

USER MODEL: APP/USER.PHP

use Illuminate\Notifications\Notifiable;

class User extends Authenticatable
{
    use Notifiable;
}



UNDERLYING MECHANISM

When a notification is created, Laravel follows an Eloquent-driven approach
where it persists the notification, instead of just storing it in a collection.
It utilizes the Illuminate\Notifications\DatabaseNotification model.

STORING NOTIFICATIONS

In the background, Laravel fulfills these three main steps to store
notifications in the database:

 1. Preparing the Model: It sets up the notification model with necessary
    attributes.
 2. Saving it in the Database: Utilizes Eloquent methods (create, for example)
    to store the record.
 3. Filling the ID: Once it's saved in the database, it assigns the notification
    a unique identifier.


NOTIFICATIONS TABLE STRUCTURE

 * id: Unique notification identifier.
 * type: Notification class name.
 * notifiable_id: User ID for user notifications (the "id" column from
   respective notifiable entity).
 * notifiable_type: Type of notifiable entity (e.g., "App\Models\User").
 * data: Core notification content.
 * read_at: Timestamp when the user marked the notification as read.
 * timestamps: Auto-handled "created_at" and "updated_at" fields.


NOTIFICATIONS AND DATABASE IN LARAVEL

 * Laravel offers a flexible and consistent approach to persisting notifications
   in a database.
 * It handles much of the underlying setup automatically, combining with
   Eloquent's powerful features.
 * It complements in-memory storage by providing a more permanent option.

The notification system in Laravel provides a unified approach to send messages
across disparate communication channels, such as SMS, email, and Slack.


CUSTOM CHANNEL CREATION

Let's suppose, you want a notification system that sends a notification to a
"Web Portal" in addition to the standard email, sms and slack channels. You will
need to follow these steps:

 1. Define a Notification Channel: Create a class that extends the
    Illuminate\Notifications\Notification base class.

 2. Routing: Define a routeNotificationForWebPortal method in your notifiable
    entity (e.g., User model) returning the destination of the channel.

 3. Custom Delivery Logic: You can customize how notifications are delivered to
    this channel by defining a send method in your notification class.


CODE TO IMPLEMENT

Here is the Laravel PHP code:

NOTIFICATION CHANNEL CLASS

Create a new PHP class - WebPortalChannel.php:

namespace App\Channels;

use Illuminate\Notifications\Notification;

class WebPortalChannel
{
    public function send($notifiable, Notification $notification)
    {
        // Custom delivery logic goes here
    }
}


NOTIFIABLE TRAIT

In your notifiable model (User.php), integrate the trait and specify
routeNotificationForWebPortal:

namespace App\Models;

use Illuminate\Notifications\Notifiable;
use Illuminate\Foundation\Auth\User as Authenticatable;

class User extends Authenticatable
{
    use Notifiable;

    public function routeNotificationForWebPortal()
    {
        return $this->web_portal_path;
    }
}


NOTIFICATION CLASS

In the notification class, you can use the WebPortalChannel and define the via
method to specify channel delivery:

use App\Channels\WebPortalChannel;
use Illuminate\Notifications\Notification;

class WebPortalNotification extends Notification
{
    public function via($notifiable)
    {
        return [WebPortalChannel::class];
    }

    public function toWebPortal($notifiable)
    {
        return [
            // Web portal specific message data
        ];
    }
}


SERVICE PROVIDER

Add everything in App\Providers\AppServiceProvider.

use App\Channels\WebPortalChannel;
use Illuminate\Support\Facades\Notification;
use Illuminate\Support\ServiceProvider;

class AppServiceProvider extends ServiceProvider
{
    public function boot()
    {
        Notification::extend('webportal', function ($app) {
            return $app->make(WebPortalChannel::class);
        });
    }
}
